## Picking Up From Day 1

Yesterday I got my first real look at what GRC means as a whole. Today the focus narrowed to the first pillar — **Governance** — and honestly it turned out to be more interesting than I expected. I went in thinking governance just meant policies and paperwork. I came out thinking it is really about leadership, culture, and accountability. Those are very different things.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Governance, at its core, is about answering one question: *who is responsible for making sure this organization operates responsibly?*

It is the combination of leadership decisions, written policies, and defined frameworks that tell everyone in an organization what is expected of them — especially when it comes to protecting sensitive information. In cybersecurity terms, governance is what ensures security is not just an IT problem that gets handed off to one team. It is an organizational responsibility that starts at the top.

The way I am thinking about it now:

- **Leadership** decides that security matters and backs that up with real investment and attention
- **Policies** put those decisions in writing so everyone knows what the rules are
- **Frameworks** like NIST or HIPAA give organizations a structured way to organize and measure their governance efforts

Without all three working together, governance is just a word.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The phrase "tone at the top" came up a lot today and it genuinely stuck with me.

The idea is simple: if the people leading an organization treat security as a priority, that attitude filters down through every level. If they treat it as a box to check or an IT team's problem, that attitude filters down too — and it does a lot more damage.

I thought back to things I have seen at past workplaces. I remember an IT Director who would regularly bring up phishing risks in team meetings — not in a scary way, just keeping it visible and normal. People paid more attention because of it. I also remember seeing a leader once dismiss a legitimate security concern because it felt inconvenient at the time. The team noticed. After that, people were a lot more hesitant to raise issues. One moment, one decision — and it quietly shaped how the whole team behaved for months.

That is what tone at the top actually looks like in practice. It is not a policy document. It is behavior. And it compounds over time in either direction.

---

## Applying This to OpenMRS on AWS

In a real OpenMRS deployment, governance does not happen automatically. Someone has to own it.

That means clearly assigning roles like **System Owner** and **Information System Security Officer (ISSO)** — actual people with actual accountability, not just job titles on an org chart. It means documented policies that cover things like who can access patient data, how that access is reviewed, and what happens when something goes wrong. It means leadership scheduling regular reviews instead of setting a policy once and forgetting it exists.

For an open-source EHR system handling real patient data on AWS, the governance layer is what keeps everything else honest. Risk management and compliance both depend on it. If governance is weak, everything downstream suffers.

---

## What I Am Still Thinking About

Something I am still working through: how does governance actually function in smaller healthcare organizations that do not have a dedicated CISO or security leadership team? In a large hospital system it is easier to imagine — there are resources, there are roles, there is budget. But what about a small clinic running OpenMRS with a tiny IT team?

I do not have a clear answer yet. But I think it is an important question, especially because OpenMRS is widely used in under-resourced healthcare settings around the world. Governance cannot just be designed for well-funded environments. I want to think more about this as the project develops.

